english:
  title: Audience at the Great Hall
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The great hall opens wide, dawn's chill descends,
    Banners flutter high against the jade balustrade.
    Clouds part above the sacred throne—I hear celestial voice,
    Spring floods the cups of rosy mist as we offer joy to the sage.

    All six realms become one household under Yao's sun and moon,
    Thrice ten thousand voices cry 'Long live!'—the robes of Han renewed.
    Yet I cannot fathom where this body stands in time,
    It seems I've mounted the blue phoenix toward the jade expanse.
  footnotes:
    - The 'great hall' refers to the Myeongdang (明堂), the traditional ceremonial hall of state, suggesting a royal audience or court ceremony.
    - References to Yao and Han evoke legendary sage-kings and dynastic continuity, expressing the wish that the current reign embodies the virtues of ancient rulership.
    - The final image of the blue phoenix and jade expanse suggests the speaker's spirit being lifted into transcendence, perhaps expressing the overwhelming majesty of the occasion or transcendence of mundane consciousness.
